 housing, and jobs away from poor black people turned ghettos and prisons into social pandemics. Americans in the North made this history. They tried to unmake it, too. Liberalism, rather than lighting the way to vanquish the darkness of the Jim Crow North gave racism new and complex places to hide. The twelve original essays in this anthology unveil Jim Crow’s many strange careers in the North. They accomplish two goals: first, they show how the Jim Crow North worked as a system to maintain social, economic, and political inequality in the nation’s most liberal places; and second, they chronicle how activists worked to undo the legal, economic, and social inequities born of Northern Jim Crow policies, practices, and ideas. The book ultimately dispels the myth that the South was the birthplace of American racism, and presents a compelling argument that American racism actually originated in the North.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSegregationxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans-Civil rights-History-20th century. 0aAfrican Americans-Segregation-History-20th century. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movements-United States-History-20th century. 0aMiddle West-Race relations-History-20th century. 0aNortheastern States-Race relations-History-20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism-United States-History-20th century. 0aUnited States-Race relations-History-20th century. 0aWest (U.S.)-Race relations-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aBarr, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckett, Balthazar I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a